  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does RBI design Indian currency notes?",
  "response": "The design of Indian currency notes is a meticulous process overseen by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) in collaboration with the Government of India. The process involves several stages and considerations to ensure security, aesthetic appeal, and functionality. Here\u2019s an overview of how RBI designs Indian currency notes:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Authority and Legal Framework**\n- The RBI Act, 1934, empowers the Reserve Bank of India to issue and manage currency notes, except for the one-rupee note, which is issued by the Government of India.\n- The design and features of currency notes are finalized in consultation with the Central Government and other stakeholders.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Key Design Considerations**\nThe design of currency notes focuses on:\n- **Security Features**: To prevent counterfeiting and ensure authenticity.\n- **Aesthetic Elements**: To reflect India\u2019s cultural, historical, and economic identity.\n- **Functionality**: To ensure durability, ease of use, and accessibility for all sections of society.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Design Process**\n#### **a. Theme and Concept**\n- The design is based on a theme that represents India\u2019s heritage, diversity, and achievements.\n- For example, the Mahatma Gandhi (MG) series features the portrait of Mahatma Gandhi, while other elements highlight India\u2019s monuments, flora, fauna, and cultural symbols.\n\n#### **b. Security Features**\nAdvanced security features are incorporated to prevent counterfeiting. These include:\n- **Intaglio Printing**: Raised printing used for the portrait of Mahatma Gandhi.\n- **Watermark**: A transparent image visible when held against light.\n- **Security Thread**: A thread embedded in the note that glows under UV light.\n- **Latent Image**: A hidden image visible only at a certain angle.\n- **Microlettering**: Tiny text printed on the note.\n- **Fluorescence**: Ink that glows under ultraviolet light.\n- **Optically Variable Ink (OVI)**: Ink that changes color when viewed from different angles.\n\n#### **c. Visual Elements**\n- **Portrait**: Mahatma Gandhi\u2019s portrait is a common feature on all modern Indian notes.\n- **Language Panel**: Denomination in 15 of the 22 official languages of India.\n- **Motifs and Symbols**: Depictions of Indian monuments, historical sites, and cultural symbols.\n- **Flora and Fauna**: Representations of India\u2019s biodiversity.\n\n#### **d. Size and Color**\n- Each denomination has a distinct size and color to aid identification and prevent confusion.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Production Process**\n- **Printing**: Currency notes are printed at four dedicated printing presses: \n  - The Security Printing and Minting Corporation of India (SPMCIL) presses in Nashik and Dewas.\n  - The Bharatiya Reserve Bank Note Mudran Private Ltd (BRBNMPL) presses in Mysuru and Salboni.\n- **Paper**: Special currency paper made from cotton and cotton rag is used for durability.\n- **Ink**: Special inks with unique properties like fluorescence and OVI are used.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Testing and Approval**\n- Prototype designs are rigorously tested for security, durability, and usability.\n- The final design is approved by the RBI and the Central Government before mass production.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Introduction and Circulation**\n- New currency notes are introduced into circulation through the RBI\u2019s network of banks and cash handling systems.\n- Public awareness campaigns are conducted to educate users about new designs and security features.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Regular Updates**\n- The RBI periodically updates the design of currency notes to incorporate advanced security features and reflect contemporary themes.\n\n---\n\nThe design of Indian currency notes is a blend of art, technology, and security, aimed at fostering trust in the monetary system while celebrating India\u2019s rich heritage.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
